            "id": "174eeaefebfc49e0b9653",
            "questionText": "Imagine a space elevator extending from the Earth's surface ($!$radius = 6.371 \\times 10^6 \\text{ m}$!$) to geostationary orbit ($!$radius = 4.2164 \\times 10^7 \\text{ m}$!$). An engineer wants to lift a ($!$m = 1000 \\text{ kg}$!$) research module up the elevator. Calculate the change in gravitational potential energy ($!$\\Delta E_p$!$) of the module as it is moved from the Earth's surface to geostationary orbit. The mass of Earth is ($!$M = 5.972 \\times 10^{24} \\text{ kg}$!$) and the gravitational constant is ($!$G = 6.674 \\times 10^{-11} \\text{ N m}^2 \\text{ kg}^{-2}$!$).",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "2bddb80cd6a54bd8b78f1",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula that correctly represents the change in gravitational potential energy when moving a mass between two radial distances. Which of the following expressions would you select?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ba8a45fb-f342-4482-89ac-8d8dbc50f532",
                        "3e125180-5cf1-4f7b-a223-cc1bda7f1317"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta E_p = -\\frac{GMm}{r} + \\frac{GMm}{r_0}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\Delta E_p = GMm \\left(\\frac{1}{r_0} - \\frac{1}{r}\\right)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E_p = \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 - \\frac{GMm}{r}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = \\frac{GMm}{r^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "157ddf942ea4487bbdf0a",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that the formula has been identified, let\u2019s compute the multiplication constant $!$GMm$!$. Using the given values for $!$G$!$, $!$M$!$, and $!$m$!$, calculate this constant.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "3.985e17"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "J\u00b7m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ba8a45fb-f342-4482-89ac-8d8dbc50f532"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "47c9c5bdc8144efa9501d",
                    "stepText": "Next, determine the difference between the reciprocals of the two radial distances, $!$\\frac{1}{R_e}$!$ and $!$\\frac{1}{r_{geo}}$!$. Calculate $!$\\left(\\frac{1}{R_e} - \\frac{1}{r_{geo}\\right)$!$ using the provided values.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.331e-7"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m^-1",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ba8a45fb-f342-4482-89ac-8d8dbc50f532"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "5d18b025bf19411c929f3",
                    "stepText": "Finally, combine your results from the previous steps by multiplying the constant from Step 2 and the reciprocal difference from Step 3. This product gives you the change in gravitational potential energy $!$\\Delta E_p$!$. Compute this final value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
